definitions.definition: To tabulate ; to put into a table or grid.
To supply (a guest, client etc.) with food at a table; to feed .
To delineate ; to represent , as in a picture; to depict .
To put on the table of a commission or legislative assembly; to propose for formal discussion or consideration , to put on the agenda.
To remove from the agenda, to postpone dealing with; to shelve ( to indefinitely postpone consideration or discussion of something ) .
examples: The legislature tabled the amendment, so they will not be discussing it until later.
The motion was tabled, ensuring that it would not be taken up until a later date.

definitions.definition: To represent a company or organization (at an exposition , fair, etc.), usually at a booth or display .
To join (pieces of timber) together using coaks .
To show one's cards face-up, especially during showdown .
To make board hems in the skirts and bottoms of (sails) in order to strengthen them in the part attached to the bolt-rope .

main_definition: To tabulate ; to put into a table or grid. [from 15th c.]
secondary_definitions: ( now rare ) To supply (a guest, client etc.) with food at a table; to feed . [from 15th c.]
( obsolete ) To delineate ; to represent , as in a picture; to depict . [17th–19th c.]
( non-US ) To put on the table of a commission or legislative assembly; to propose for formal discussion or consideration , to put on the agenda. [from 17th c.]
( chiefly US ) To remove from the agenda, to postpone dealing with; to shelve ( to indefinitely postpone consideration or discussion of something ) . [from 19th c.]
( metonymic ) To represent a company or organization (at an exposition , fair, etc.), usually at a booth or display .
( carpentry , obsolete ) To join (pieces of timber) together using coaks . [18th–19th c.]
To put on a table. [from 19th c.]
( poker , colloquial ) To show one's cards face-up, especially during showdown .
( nautical ) To make board hems in the skirts and bottoms of (sails) in order to strengthen them in the part attached to the bolt-rope .
